# TypeScript conventions

## Pure modules first

`lib/*.ts` files should be pure: no DOM access, no globals, no side effects.
Take inputs, return outputs. This makes them trivially unit-testable and
trivially reasoned about by AI tooling.

```ts
// BAD: reaches into the DOM, hard to test
export function clampScaleFromElement(el: HTMLElement): number { ... }

// GOOD: pure, easy to spec
export function clampScale(scale: number, min = 0.25, max = 4): number {
  return Math.min(Math.max(scale, min), max);
}
```

## Immutable data flow

Functions that operate on `MultigraphData` (or any shared state) must return
a new object rather than mutating. This unlocks undo/redo, time-travel debugging,
and Svelte 5 fine-grained reactivity.

```ts
// BAD
export function moveNode(data: MultigraphData, id: string, p: Point) {
  data.posByNodeId[id] = p;
}

// GOOD
export function moveNode(data: MultigraphData, id: string, p: Point): MultigraphData {
  return { ...data, posByNodeId: { ...data.posByNodeId, [id]: p } };
}
```

## Configurable, not constant

When a function depends on a tuning value (radius, falloff, threshold, etc.),
make it a parameter with a default — never read a constant directly. This
makes it pinnable in tests.

```ts
export function scaleByHops(hops: number, falloff = 0.7, min = 0.1): number {
  return Math.max(min, falloff ** hops);
}
```

### Pin new fields when extending a config interface

When you add a field to a settings interface like `LayoutSettings` and
give it a default in the central `withDefault…` helper, every existing
test that builds a `Partial<…>` settings literal silently picks up the
new default. If that default changes layout/physics/render behavior,
those tests can break in ways that have nothing to do with the field
itself.

In the same commit that adds the field:

- Grep for the interface (`rg LayoutSettings -t ts`) and for partial
  literals passed as `settings: { … }` in spec/story files.
- For each call site, decide whether the new default is right for that
  test and either keep it (no change) or **pin** the field to the value
  the test previously relied on (often `0` for a strength/iterations
  knob, or the pre-existing baked-in constant).

This keeps the new behavior opt-in for existing tests and isolates the
new field's effects to the specs you wrote for it.

## Types live in shared files

- Shared types: `apps/mind-map-sv/src/lib/components/ui/types/*.ts`
- Module-local types: defined inline at the top of the consuming `.ts` file
- Don't re-define `NodeData` / `EdgeData` / `MultigraphData` / `Point` — import them.

## No `any`, no `as` casts without a comment

If you have to assert a type, leave a one-line comment explaining why the
type system can't see it.

## File naming

- Pure modules: `camelCase.ts` (e.g. `graphMath.ts`, `hitTest.ts`)
- Specs: same name + `.spec.ts` (e.g. `graphMath.spec.ts`)
- Test fixtures: `testFixtures.ts`
- Type-only files: `singularNoun.ts` in a `types/` folder
